social_posts.post_text: Aloha Lā Kūʻokoʻa. Glad all eyes were on Hawai`i yesterday. Taken from >20 miles away.

I dreamt of fire the night the eruption started. I know these events can cause anxiety to folks who have experienced loss. I still feel grief and sadness but it is humbling to be in the presence of creation and destruction. Its also interesting to hear the perspectives of visitors who only experience this temporarily. Not sure if i’m jealous but this is home.
Getting lost looking at layers of rocks like stars.
I heard there were lava boats and I had to see it for myself. Taken pre-TFR.

Sei whales are rarely seen in Hawaii possibly due to blending in with humpbacks and lack of whale watching tours venturing off shore. We went out in search of false killer whales but found sei whales, sperm whales and rissos dolphins instead. Probably the best combination of species we’ve had in a very long time. Not possible without the help of @captainzodiackona. We have sighting catalogs of all of these species and look forward to hopefully finding matches to learn more about these elusive species in Hawaiian waters.
sunrise sperm whales. one of my favorite places to be during humpback season is in deep water. iykyk. taken under permit 26596.

Mixed group of pilot whales and melon-headed whales. This was my first time seeing them milling together like this. 99% of folks in Hawaiʻi will never see these animals despite them being just offshore but we still advocate for their protection! This was taken under permit 20605!

Glassy water, cooperative animals and entanglement hazards. Nice of these bottlenose dolphins to lead us to a discarded towing hawser. We removed it and a few other nets this project! Video taken under NFMS Permit.
Some of my favorite bird photos from this past month working with @captainzodiackona and @cascadiaresearch.

Episode 20 of @wildandunprotected is live!

Sign From Nature (Manuohina) with Jordan Lerma @uheheu of @cascadiaresearch 
What a guest to have for our 20th episode. 

This episode is jam packed. Talking about whether or not college educations should still be a thing in 15 years to boat yoga…and everything in between. This episode has it all. 

The “wild” stories part of the show will make you smile, shed a tear, and say what is this show…all in one segment.  
Enjoy and let us know what you think!

We spend hours searching and waiting for moments like this. Ziphius cavirostris, also known as Cuvier’s beaked whale or the goose-beaked whale, holds the record for the deepest and longest dive (with some caveats). During an encounter last week, we waited 70 minutes for the animals to surface, which lasted less than 20 seconds before they embarked on another 70-minute dive. During these dive intervals, everyone on the boat is required to scan and be on alert. We get so few opportunities to get close, and we have to make the most of these moments. Research done under NMFS permit.

We spent 17 days on the water covering almost 2000km off Hawaiʻi Island and had 37 encounters with 11 different species of whales and dolphins. I’ll try to share more photos from this project over the next week or so. This is a juvenile pantropical spotted dolphin. In calm seas they can be seen from over 2km away thanks to these big leaps to remove remoras. They are often approachable and like to ride the bow wake from our boat. Taken under NMFS permit 26596.

Typically we only find parts of squid after they are brought up and eaten by marine mammals. Coming into the harbor during our project Cory spotted one that was discarded by a fishing boat. We still collected it so that the students at Parker school can dissect and determine species based on the beak. We also got to watch it flash its chromatophores!
